Fill a large #saucepan{} with the boiling water from your #kettle{}. Bring back to the
boil on high heat.

Meanwhile, chop the @potatoes{450%g} into 2cm chunks (no need to peel) and add to
the saucepan with half the @ground turmeric{1} and a pinch of @salt{}. Cook until
you can easily slip a knife through, ~{10-12%mins}, then drain in a #colander{}
and allow to steam-dry for a few seconds before returning to the pan (off the
heat). Keep warm with the #lid{} on.

Meanwhile, chop the @paneer{250%g} into 2cm chunks. Halve, peel and finely slice
the @echalion shallot{1}. Halve the @red chilli{1/2} lengthways, deseed then
finely chop. Chop the @premium tomato mix{125%g} in half (or leave them whole if
you prefer). Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a large #frying pan{} on medium-high
heat, once hot add the paneer to the pan and fry until golden, stirring
occasionally, ~{3-4%mins}.

Stir the shallot into the paneer and cook until starting to soften,
~{2-3%mins}.

> TIP: Add a drizzle of oil if the pan looks dry.

Stir in the @ginger puree{1/2}(easy ginger), @North Indian style spice mix{1},
remaining @ground turmeric{1}, a pinch of chilli (careful - you can always add
more later!) and the cherry tomatoes and cook for ~{30%seconds} before stirring
in the @water{100%ml}.

Bring to the boil then reduce the heat to a simmer.

Stir the @baby spinach{125%g} in a handful at a time until wilted,
~{1-2%mins}, then stir through the @mango chutney{40%g}.

Season the saag paneer to taste with salt, @ground black pepper{} and a pinch
more chilli if needed. Stir the @nigella seeds{1} through the potatoes.

Serve the Bombay potatoes in #bowls{} topped with the saag paneer. Finish with a
sprinkle of more red chilli if liked. ENJOY!